a.title: Perform simple state searches of the PLANTS database.
Perform complex searches of the PLANTS Database.
Learn more about searching for plants on the PLANTS web site.
The Alternative Crops Module. An easy way to learn more about crops suitable for small scale farming by limited-resource farmers, small landowners, and homeowners.
A list of plants with expanded plant characteristic information.

View and download the taxonomic hierarchy for any plant, or the entire classification for North American non-vascular plants and lichens or U.S. vascular plants. Entries are linked to PLANTS profiles for easy access to more information.
List of commonly used cover crops, with links to profile pages.
Information about culturally significant plants, including usage, management, and cultural importance.
Please help us improve the PLANTS database by sharing information about where plants grow in the U.S.
Documents related to the PLANTS database
Plants for which we have conservation information including: establishment and growth, suitable uses, and appearance.
Lists of introduced, invasive, state-listed noxious, and federally-listed noxious plants, with thousands of links to species abstracts, identification guides, and control measures.
PLANTS Threatened and Endangered lists provide access to state and federally protected plants.
View the plants on the National Wetland Plant List.
View more than 50,000 plant images.
The complete PLANTS list is nearly 7 MB and includes the symbol, scientific name, accepted name for synonyms or common name for accepted names, and family.
State PLANTS Checklists include Symbol, Synonym Symbol, Scientific Name with Authors, National Common Name, and Family.
Download search results generated by the Advanced Search.
Symbols for Unknown PLANTS includes Symbols and descriptive Common Names for generic categories.
NRCS personnel and cooperators can download an NRCS State GSAT List.
NRCS personnel and cooperators can download an NRCS State Plants List.
The Crop Nutrient Uptake Tool provides estimates of nutrient removal by crops at various levels, such as the farm, conservation district, and watershed level.
